<div>
    <h3>{{ _('GitFiles settings') }}</h3>
    <div style="clear:both">
        See the <a href="https://github.com/OutsourcedGuru/OctoPrint-GitFiles" target="_blank">README.md</a> for how to setup your repository.
        By default, the path for your files within OctoPrint will
        be <code>~/.octoprint/uploads/gitfiles</code> as a subfolder. This would be the safest option if you expect to simply 
        upload files straight to OctoPrint later.<br/><br/>
        Otherwise, you can directly use the <code>uploads</code> folder itself by entering that in the Path field below. Note that this
        option could result in git merge issues for you. If you know what you're doing, this may offer you some flexibility.<br/><br/>
    </div>
    <form class="form-horizontal">
        <div class="control-group">
            <label class="control-label">{{ _('URL:') }}</label>
            <div class="controls">
                <input type="text" class="input-block-level" data-bind="value: settings.plugins.gitfiles.url">
            </div>
        </div>
        <div class="control-group">
            <label class="control-label">{{ _('Path:') }}</label>
            <div class="controls">
                <input type="text" class="input-block-level" data-bind="value: settings.plugins.gitfiles.path">
            </div>
        </div>
    </form>
    <table><tr><td valign="top"><h3>{{ _('General workflow') }}</h3>
        <ol>
            <li>Into your workstation's local repository, slice the latest version of your files as gcode.</li>
            <li>In this same folder on your workstation:
                <ul><li><code>git add .</code></li><li><code>git commit -m "Commit-related information"</code></li><li><code>git push</code></li></ul></li>
            <li>In OctoPrint, press the Github icon button to pull from the repository and wait for the latest version to download.</li>
        </ol>
        <p>If you earlier set up the Path to coincide with <b>uploads</b> and unless you are good with command-line git, it's best to not upload files directly to OctoPrint using the Files side panel feature.</p>
</div>
